@node Intro "Introduction" 
 
                         Introduction 
 
    Thank you for purchasing AccuPoint TCS for WACOM Tablets! Welcome 
    to the growing number of creative people who have added a tablet 
    to their graphics toolbox. Your tablet hardware is manufactured 
    by WACOM, a company known worldwide for their superior computer 
    graphics products. Until recently, only users of IBM and 
    Macintosh computers had access to WACOM tablets. We at TriMedia 
    are proud to have the opportunity to bring their unique blend of 
    value and high performance to the Amiga user. The software 
    included with your tablet was written by TriMedia, Inc. and we 
    will provide technical support free of charge. If you should have 
    any problem with your tablet, please check the manual first. The 
    answers to most questions can be found in these pages. If your 
    problem remains, call us at our technical support number (see the 
    section titled @{" If you need assistance " link Assistance} later in this manual). We 
    will make every effort to resolve any problems you may have. 
 
    In a few moments we'll tell you how to get your tablet set up and 
    running with your Amiga. But first, please take a moment to fill 
    out and return your registration card. This will allow us to keep 
    you informed of future upgrades and enhancements to the AccuPoint 
    software. Returning your card will also help us to better serve 
    you if you should need to contact us. So please do return your 
    card now. And again, thank you for purchasing a TriMedia tablet 
    driver! 
@endnode 
@node Box "What's in the Box" 
 
                            What's in the Box 
 
    Your AccuPoint software kit should include one each of the 
    following: 
 
        · AccuPoint Software Diskette 
        · The User's Guide 
        · Registration Card 
 
    If you are missing any parts contact your dealer at once! 
@endnode 
@node Basics "Some Tablet Basics and Terminology" 
 
                     Some Tablet Basics and Terminology 
 
    PLEASE DO NOT SKIP THIS SECTION! 
 
    Your WACOM graphics tablet is a high resolution graphics 
    digitizer. With a tablet and a paint program you can trace 
    existing artwork or graphics from paper onto the Amiga screen. 
    You will find that a tablet is the perfect companion to a CAD, 3D 
    or structured drawing program such as Gold Disk's Professional 
    Draw. Additionally, those of you who come from a conventional 
    media background will appreciate the more natural feel of the 
    Stylus (pen) when compared to the Amiga's standard mouse for 
    freehand drawing. 
 
    The tablet system consists of two main components, the "Stylus" 
    and the "Tablet" itself. Depending on the tablet model you own, 
    you may also have a "Cursor" which resembles a mouse with a clear 
    cross-hair on its front. Both the Stylus and Cursor control the 
    mouse pointer in a similar manner. The tablet contains a grid of 
    wires which sense the position of the Stylus relative its 
    surface. These wires are located under the large, slightly 
    recessed, area in the center of the tablet. This area is known as 
    the Active Area. The tablet can only sense the Stylus's position 
    in the Active Area. It is not necessary for the Stylus to 
    actually touch the surface of the Tablet. As long as the Pen is 
    within about 1/4 inch of the the Tablet's surface, the Tablet can 
    lock on to its position. Whenever the Pen is close enough to the 
    Tablet for it to sense its position, the Pen is said to be in 
    Proximity. 
 
    The Stylus has either 1 or 2 switches (again, depending on 
    model). One switch is located in the tip of the Stylus. This is 
    called the Tip Switch. You activate the tip switch by pressing 
    down on the Stylus against the Tablet. As shipped, the tip switch 
    is set to function just like the Amiga's LEFT mouse button. If 
    you have the non-pressure sensitive Stylus, you also have 1 Side 
    Switch which initially functions just like the Amiga's RIGHT 
    mouse button. You will see later how you can use the @{" APConfig " link Configuring} 
    program to change the functions performed by the switches. 
 
    If you have the Pressure-Sensitive Stylus, you have only the tip 
    switch (which is also the pressure sensor). In this case, 
    AccuPoint allows you to use a "qualifier" key on the keyboard to 
    activate the menus. This key is user-selectable in APConfig. It 
    is initially set to the <Left-Alt> key. To use an Amiga menu, 
    hold down the <Left-Alt> key and press the Tip Switch of the 
    stylus against the tablet's active area. Instead of selecting an 
    icon or window, this will activate the menu bar as if you had 
    pressed the right mouse button. 
 
    It is important to note that the tablet only sends signals to the 
    Amiga when the stylus is in proximity. Therefore, pressing or 
    releasing the stylus's buttons when it is out of proximity will 
    not have any effect. Always be sure to have the stylus in 
    proximity while doing button operations. 
@endnode 
@node Hardware "Tablet Hardware Installation" 
 
                        Tablet Hardware Installation 
 
    NOTE: See the WACOM tablet hardware manual for important details 
    on your particular tablet model. 
 
    1. Turn your Amiga and Tablet off. 
 
    2. Set the tablet's DIP switches. See the WACOM tablet hardware 
    manual for the location and layout of the tablet's DIP switches. 
    AccuPoint requires that the DIP switches be set to the factory 
    default settings. If you have just purchased your tablet (new) 
    you should not have to change any of these settings. 
 
    3. Plug the tablet's serial cable into the connector on the 
    tablet (i.e. labeled RS-232C). 
 
    4. Plug the 25-pin end of the tablet's serial cable into the 
    Amiga's serial port. If your tablet came with only a 9-pin cable 
    you will need a DB9M to DB25F adapter (available at any Radio 
    Shack or computer store). If you have an Amiga 1000 computer, you 
    will need a 25 pin, male to male gender changer (available at any 
    Radio Shack or computer store). 
 
    5. Make the necessary power connections as described in the WACOM 
    tablet hardware manual. 
 
    6. Power up the Amiga and the WACOM tablet. 
 
    Congratulations! Your tablet hardware is installed. 
    Proceed to the section titled @{" AccuPoint Software Installation " link Software}. 
@endnode 
@node Software "AccuPoint Software Installation" 
 
                     AccuPoint Software Installation 
 
    Note that AccuPoint REQUIRES Amiga OS Release 2.0 or greater! 
 
    Before proceeding, make a backup copy of the AccuPoint software 
    diskette. Then put the original diskette in a safe place and use 
    the backup as your working copy. 
 
    IMPORTANT: Before making your backup copy be sure that your 
    original disk is Write Protected. To do so slide the small black 
    write protect "switch" on the underside of the AccuPoint diskette 
    to the Write PROTECT position. You should be able to see through 
    the little square hole uncovered by the switch when the disk is 
    write protected. 
 
    You can find complete instructions for copying diskettes in your 
    Amiga User's Manual or see the instructions below. 
 
    I. Making a Backup from Workbench 
 
        1. Place the AccuPoint diskette in one of your Amiga's disk 
        drives. 
 
        2. Select Copy from the Workbench's Icons menu. Follow the 
        instructions on screen, inserting the AccuPoint diskette when 
        asked for the "Source Disk" or "From Disk", and a blank 
        diskette when asked for the "Target Disk" or "Destination 
        Disk". 
 
        3. When the disk copy process is finished, remove the "Copy 
        of " from the beginning of your backup disk's name using the 
        rename function. Click once on the icon for your backup 
        AccuPoint disk to select it. Select Rename from the Icons 
        menu. A window will appear displaying the disk's name. Using 
        the arrow and backspace keys delete the letters "Copy of " 
        from the disk's name and press the RETURN key. NOTE: Be sure 
        to delete the trailing space between "Copy of" and the 
        AccuPoint disk's name. 
 
    See your Amiga manual for more details on disk copying. 
 
 
    II. Making a Backup from the Shell or CLI 
 
        1. At the Shell or CLI prompt, type: 
             DiskCopy df0: TO df0: 
 
        or, if you have an external drive on an Amiga 500, 1000 or 
        1200, type: 
            DiskCopy df0: TO df1: 
 
        or, if you have an external drive on an Amiga 2000, 2500, 
        3000 or 4000, type: 
            DiskCopy df0: TO df2: 
 
        2. Follow the instructions on screen, inserting the AccuPoint 
        diskette when asked for the "Source Disk" or "From Disk", and 
        a blank diskette when asked for the "Target Disk" or 
        "Destination Disk". 
 
    See your Amiga manual for more details on the shell and disk 
    copying. 
 
 
    III. Installing the AccuPoint driver and APConfig 
 
    This release of the AccuPoint software includes Commodore's Amiga 
    Installer. Installer automates the process of installing a 
    software product, asking you for your preferences according to 
    your knowledge of the Amiga. Installer provides extensive help 
    facilities should you need them or are just curious. We STRONGLY 
    suggest you use Installer to install the AccuPoint software. 
 
    You can run the AccuPoint software from its own disk, but you 
    will probably want to install it on your Workbench disk, hard 
    disk, or on your paint or drawing program's disk. 
 
        1. Place your working copy of the AccuPoint disk in a drive 
        and open it by double-clicking on its icon. 
 
        2. Now double-click on the on the APInstall icon in the 
        disk's window. 
 
        3. Follow the instructions in the Installer window to copy 
        the AccuPoint software from the AccuPoint disk to your 
        destination disk. The Installer will allow you to make 
        choices on which software modules will be installed. If you 
        are not familiar with Amiga Installer click on the "Help" 
        gadget in each screen for an explanation of your options. 
 
    See your Amiga manual for more information on copying files. 
@endnode 
@node Running "Running the AccuPoint Driver" 
 
                     Running the AccuPoint Driver 
 
    By now you should have read the section titled @{" Some Tablet Basics " link Basics}
    , and have installed the tablet and software as explained in the 
    @{" Hardware " link Hardware} and @{" Software " link Software} sections. Also at this point the tablet 
    should be powered up. 
 
    Before you start the AccuPoint Driver for the first time you must 
    configure it for the model of tablet you have. Open the disk or 
    drawer where you put the AccuPoint software and start the tablet 
    preferences editor by double-clicking on the APConfig icon. The 
    APConfig window will open. For now you can ignore the warning 
    about the tablet driver not running. Locate the tablet type 
    gadget in the upper left of the window next to the WACOM logo, 
    see @{" Figure 2 " system "WDisplay Figure_2 TITLE Figure_2 TOP 78 LEFT 212 WIDTH 557 HEIGHT 179"}. It will initially be set to "SD-510C". You can 
    cycle through the various tablet models which AccuPoint supports 
    by repeatedly clicking on this gadget. Set the tablet type to 
    match the model which you have, and click the "Save" gadget in 
    the lower left of the APConfig window. See the section titled 
    @{" Configuring AccuPoint to Your Needs " link Configuring} for more information on the 
    APConfig program. Now let's start the tablet driver. 
 
    Open the disk or drawer where you put the AccuPoint software and 
    start the driver by double-clicking on the AccuPoint icon. A 
    small window containing version and copyright information should 
    open on your screen, see @{" Figure 1 " system "WDisplay Figure_1 TITLE Figure_1 TOP 60 LEFT 200 WIDTH 461 HEIGHT 140"}. In about 3 seconds this 
    window will close and the AccuPoint driver will be running in the 
    background. Place the stylus in proximity (within one quarter to 
    one half of an inch of the tablet's surface) and move it around 
    the tablet's active area. The mouse pointer on the Amiga's screen 
    should be following your movements on the tablet. 
 
    Try the tip and side switches (if present) on the stylus. 
    Remember, the tip switch will work like the Amiga's left mouse 
    button and the side switch (on non-pressure pens) will work like 
    the right mouse button. 
 
    Now place the Pen aside (out of proximity) for a minute and try 
    moving the Amiga's mouse. Notice that even with AccuPoint 
    running, the Amiga's mouse still works as usual as long as the 
    stylus is out of proximity. This is important to remember later, 
    as you can sometimes "paint yourself into a corner" when you 
    start to experiment with scaling. It is possible to set the 
    scaling in such a way that you cannot reach all areas of the 
    screen. If this happens, just take the Pen out of proximity and 
    use the Amiga's mouse to change your settings back to normal, or 
    to reach a menu or gadget which you can't reach with the stylus. 
 
                        Exiting AccuPoint 
 
    To shut down the AccuPoint Driver double-click on the APExit icon 
    AccuPoint is no longer in control of the Amiga's mouse pointer. 
@endnode 
@node Configuring "Configuring AccuPoint to Your Needs" 
 
                   Configuring AccuPoint to Your Needs 
 
    Your AccuPoint software includes APConfig, the AccuPoint 
    preferences editor. APConfig allows you to: 
 
        · Select the tablet type (model) you are using. 
 
        · Select the pointer type (2-Button Pen, Pressure Pen or 
        4-Button Cursor). 
 
        · Change the function of the Buttons. 
 
        · Select the "Menu Key" for use with the pressure pen. 
 
        · Adjust the pressure required to "Draw" and "Click". 
 
        · Adjust the Screen Scaling and Tablet Area allowing you to 
        enlarge or reduce as you draw. 
 
        · Adjust the Aspect Ratio to keep your drawing properly 
        proportioned on different monitors and software. 
 
        · Set AccuPoint's Priority and Data Rate to fine tune your 
        system's performance. 
 
        · Select an alternate Serial Port (if your computer is 
        equipped with a multi-port serial board). 
 
        · Switch between Absolute and Relative (Mouse Mode) 
        positioning. 
 
        · Save your preferences (the driver will automatically use 
        the saved settings the next time it is run). 
 
        @{" Running APConfig " link "APConfig"} 
        @{" Setting Your Tablet and Pointer Type " link Tablet} 
        @{" Setting the Pointer Button Functions " link Buttons} 
        @{" Setting Pressure Levels " link PressureAdjust} 
