@node APConfig "Running APConfig" 
 
                             Running APConfig 
 
    First, make sure the AccuPoint Driver is running (AccuPoint is 
    active). Double-click on the APConfig icon. The AccuPoint control 
    panel should appear in a window on your Workbench screen. See 
    @{" Figure 2 " system "WDisplay Figure_2 TITLE Figure_2 TOP 78 LEFT 212 WIDTH 557 HEIGHT 179"}. 
 
    If the AccuPoint Driver is not running when you start APConfig, 
    some gadgets will be ghosted and will not function. APConfig will 
    also display a message suggesting you Cancel, start the AccuPoint 
    driver and then re-run APConfig. However, you may adjust some of 
    the settings (such as the Serial Port) and save them to disk 
    without the driver running. 
 
                           Types of Gadgets 
 
    APConfig uses 4 types of gadgets to control its functions. Those 
    of you accustomed to Workbench 2.0 will probably be familiar with 
    these types of gadgets and may wish to skip ahead. 
 
    The four kinds of gadgets in the APConfig window are Button 
    gadgets, Cycle gadgets, Slider gadgets, and String gadgets. 
 
        · Button gadgets appear as a raised rectangle with a text 
        label describing their function. Clicking on a button gadget 
        will cause it to execute its function. If the button's label 
        ends in an ellipses such as "Pointer Options...", clicking on 
        it will open a requester to get additional information. "Use" 
        and "Pointer Options..." are examples of button gadgets. Do 
        not confuse text display boxes with button gadgets. They look 
        similar, but text display boxes have a recessed appearance 
        and do nothing when you click on them. 
 
        · Cycle gadgets look very much like button gadgets, however, 
        in addition to their text label they also have a circular 
        arrow drawn to the left of their label. This arrow indicates 
        that as you click on the gadget, you will cycle through a 
        list of choices. For example try clicking on the "Pointer 
        Select" gadget which is initially labeled "Pressure Pen". As 
        you repeatedly click on the gadget you will see its label 
        change from "Pressure Pen" to "4-Button Cursor" to "2-Button 
        Pen" and back to "Pressure Pen". Before continuing, set the 
        pointer type back to "Pressure Pen". 
 
        · Slider gadgets work in a similar manner to slide controls 
        on a piece of electronic equipment. To change the setting of 
        a slider gadget just position the mouse pointer over the Knob 
        (the small solid box in the middle of the gadget), click and 
        hold the left mouse button (or stylus tip switch), and drag 
        the knob left or right. You will notice a number to the right 
        of the slide control. This number shows the current value set 
        on the slider as you make adjustments. 
 
        · String gadgets accept entered text. The text entered may be 
        edited by using the standard Amiga editing keys. You may use 
        the left or right arrow keys to move within the line, the 
        BackSpace key to erase the character to the left, the Del key 
        to erase the character to the right, and the ^X (press the 
        control key and then the 'X' key) to erase the entire line. 
        The Ports & Modes... "Device Name" is an example of a String 
        gadget. 
@endnode 
@node Exiting "Exiting APConfig" 
 
                        Exiting APConfig 
 
    There are four button gadgets on the bottom of the APConfig 
    window, labeled: Save, Use, Try, and Cancel. Their functions are 
    as follows: 
 
        · Save: Clicking on the Save gadget will cause APConfig to 
        send the settings to the AccuPoint driver and also save them 
        to the file S:Tablet.config. These saved settings will be 
        used the next time the driver is run. APConfig will then 
        exit. 
 
        · Use: Clicking on the Use gadget will cause APConfig to send 
        the settings to the AccuPoint driver but will NOT save them 
        to disk. This will allow you to change several settings and 
        use them without overwriting the settings previously saved to 
        disk. After clicking on Use, APConfig will exit. 
 
        · Try: Clicking on the Try gadget performs the same function 
        as Use, except APConfig will send the settings to the 
        AccuPoint driver but will NOT save them to disk and will NOT 
        exit. This allows you to change several settings without 
        having them take effect one at a time. As you make changes to 
        your settings, remember to click on Try to see their effect. 
 
        · Cancel: (Cancel undoes any "Trys" you have done) To abandon 
        any changes you have made and quit APConfig, click on the 
        Cancel gadget in the lower right corner of the window. 
        Clicking on Cancel will not send your new settings to the 
        AccuPoint Driver, and will undo any "Trys" you have done. If 
        you want to use your new settings click on Save or Use 
 
    APConfig initially shows you the settings which the driver is 
    using at the time you start APConfig. Therefore you will find 
    that if you quit APConfig and later re-start it, it will always 
    be "in-sync" with the driver. If the AccuPoint driver is not 
    running, APConfig will show you the settings saved in the file 
    S:Tablet.config. If no settings have been saved, the default 
    settings will be displayed. If your settings file is ever 
    damaged, just delete it and run APConfig and save a new file to 
    get back to the factory defaults. 
@endnode 
@node Tablet "Setting Your Tablet and Pointer Type" 
 
                   Setting Your Tablet and Pointer Type 
 
    If you have purchased your tablet as part of a TriMedia package 
    for the Amiga, you probably won't need to change these settings. 
    However if you purchased the AccuPoint TCS software separately 
    (IBM or Macintosh tablet owners) or if you have a cursor or 
    non-pressure pen, you will want to change some of these settings 
    from time to time. 
 
    In the upper left hand corner of the APConfig window (next to the 
    tablet logo, see @{" Figure 2 " system "WDisplay Figure_2 TITLE Figure_2 TOP 78 LEFT 212 WIDTH 557 HEIGHT 179"}) you will find two cycle gadgets, one 
    below the other. These are the Tablet Type and Pointer Select 
    gadgets. 
 
    The Tablet Type gadget is initially labeled "SD-510C". Clicking 
    on it will cycle through the list of WACOM tablets supported by 
    AccuPoint. Find your tablet model by clicking on this gadget. 
    Note that some models are represented by a "series" number, so 
    you may not find your exact model number. For example, an SD-420E 
    tablet would be selected by choosing the SD-42x setting. 
 
    The Pointer Select gadget is initially labeled Pressure Pen. 
    Clicking on it will cycle through the list of pointers supported 
    by the tablet. Your choices will vary depending on your tablet 
    model. Try clicking on this gadget to see the Pens and Cursors 
    supported by your tablet. 
@endnode 
@node Buttons "Setting Pointer Options" 
 
                     Setting Pointer Options 
 
    The button gadget labeled "Pointer Options..." allows you to 
    assign which mouse button functions will be triggered by each 
    button on the selected pointer. If you have the Pointer type set 
    to "Pressure Pen" in the main window, you will also notice 2 
    slide controls in the right half of the Pointer Options window. 
    See the following section titled @{" Pressure Adjustments " link PressureAdjust} for 
    information on these controls and their effect on stylus use. 
 
    Clicking on Pointer Options will open a requester containing 
    cycle gadgets which allow you to assign each button on the 
    selected pointer to one of the following: See @{" Figure 3 " system "WDisplay Figure_3 TITLE Figure_3 TOP 275 LEFT 83 WIDTH 565 HEIGHT 130"}. 
 
        · Left Mouse Click 
        · Middle Mouse Click 
        · Right Mouse Click 
        · Disabled 
 
    You may be wondering about the Middle Mouse Click option. The 
    Amiga system software supports the concept of a third, middle, 
    mouse button. The system software does not use this capability 
    yet, nor do many applications. We support it for future 
    compatibility. You may also note that the number and names of 
    button assignment gadgets will vary, depending on which pointer 
    you have selected. The window will automatically adjust for the 
    currently selected pointer. 
 
    If you have the "Pressure Pen" selected in the main APConfig 
    window, you will also find a cycle gadget labeled "Menu Key:". 
    This gadget allows you to select a keyboard key which will be 
    used to activate the Amiga's menu bar. This is necessary due to 
    the fact that the pressure pen only has one button (the tip). You 
    may select from the following keys: Left or Right Shift, Left or 
    Right Alt, Left or Right Amiga, or the Control key. The default 
    Menu Key is <Left-Alt>. To use an Amiga menu, hold down the 
    <Left-Alt> key and press the Tip Switch of the stylus against the 
    tablet's active area. Instead of selecting an icon or window, 
    this will activate the menu bar as if you had pressed the right 
    mouse button. Take a moment now to get used to working with the 
    menus in this way. 
 
        NOTE: Some Amiga software (including Workbench) may use some 
        of these keys to modify mouse actions and this may cause 
        problems when trying to use one of these keys for menu 
        access. If your selection causes a conflict, try a different 
        menu key. 
 
    When you have made your selections, click on "OK" to exit the 
    requester with your changes in effect or "Cancel" to leave the 
    button assignments as they were. Remember, changes will not be 
    sent to the driver until you click on Save, Use, or Try in the 
    main window. 
@endnode 
@node PressureAdjust "Pressure Adjustments" 
 
                        Pressure Adjustments 
 
    NOTE: We strongly recommend you read and understand this section. 
    It will enable you to tailor the feel of the pressure sensitive 
    stylus to your own drawing technique. 
 
    If "Pressure Pen" is selected as the current pointer type in the 
    main APConfig window, clicking on "Pointer Options" will open a 
    requester containing two slide gadgets for pressure control, in 
    addition to the usual button assignment gadgets. See @{" Figure 3 " system "WDisplay Figure_3 TITLE Figure_3 TOP 275 LEFT 83 WIDTH 565 HEIGHT 130"}. 
 
               About Pressure Control and the Amiga 
 
    TriMedia'a AccuPoint is the first tablet driver to support 
    pressure sensitive tablets. As such, we felt it VERY important to 
    implement pressure in a way that set a standard which others 
    would have no problem following. In implementing pressure, we 
    sought and received much guidance from Commodore and other 
    developers. Most prominent of these was Electronic Arts, who made 
    DeluxePaintIV AGA the first application to support the new 
    standard. 
 
    Pressure on the Amiga has some unique features not found on other 
    systems. Most visible to the user is the idea of separate "Click" 
    and "Draw" pressures. AccuPoint allows you to set different 
    pressure levels (thresholds) for causing a Click, versus causing 
    a program to make a mark on the screen. On other systems, if you 
    like to draw with a light touch (pressure), you must be very 
    careful not to skim the tablet's surface when moving around or 
    you may accidentally drag icons or activate gadgets you don't 
    mean to. Using AccuPoint, this problem can be eliminated. 
 
    Draw Pressure 
 
    The "Draw Pressure" slide control adjusts the level of pressure 
    required to begin drawing in a pressure aware application such as 
    DPaint AGA. The higher the setting, the more pressure will be 
    needed to begin to draw. As you increase pressure above the "Draw 
    Pressure", you will see the effects of pressure as implemented in 
    the graphics program you are using. For example, in DPaint, you 
    can vary the thickness of a built-in brush, or its translucency. 
    The "Draw Pressure" must be less than or equal to the "Click 
    Pressure". If you try to set Draw Pressure higher than Click 
    Pressure, APConfig will flash the screen and force them to be 
    equal. 
 
    Click Pressure 
 
    The "Click Pressure" slide control adjusts the level of pressure 
    required to generate an Amiga mouse click (i.e. activate a 
    gadget). You will probably want this set to a fairly high level 
    to avoid accidental clicks, and drag-&-drops. The "Click 
    Pressure" must be greater than or equal to the "Draw Pressure". 
    If you try to set Click Pressure to a value lower than Draw 
    Pressure, APConfig will flash the screen and force them to be 
    equal. 
 
    NOTE: Programs which are not "pressure-aware" such as older 
    versions of DPaint, will only react to pressure above the Click 
    Pressure. In other words, non-pressure applications will act as 
    if Draw Pressure was set equal to Click Pressure. 
@endnode 
@node Scaling "The Scaling Functions" 
 
                          The Scaling Functions 
 
    AccuPoint's scaling features allow you to adjust two aspects of 
    its operation. The first of these is the ability to enlarge or 
    reduce artwork as you trace it. We will cover this function 
    first. Later you will learn how you can adjust the @{" sensitivity " link Area} 
    of the stylus to movement using one of the scaling commands. The 
    effect of adjusting the sensitivity of the stylus is similar to 
    adjusting the mouse speed in Amiga Preferences. 
 
    How AccuPoint Scaling Works 
 
    Hi-Res (high resolution) mode on the Amiga displays 640 pixels 
    across the width of the screen. In contrast, your tablet has 
    (depending on model) from 7,500 to 45,720 lines of resolution 
    (width-of-active-area in inches X 1,000, 1,270 or 2,540 lines per 
    inch). At least, more than 10 times the resolution! By using this 
    "extra" data we can enlarge an area the size of a postage stamp 
    to fill the entire screen without losing detail. At this 
    magnification, however, you need a very steady hand indeed. 
 
    The Scaling Controls 
 
    APConfig has three scaling controls, @{" Set Tablet Area... " link Area}, 
    @{"Set Screen Scaling... " link ScreenScaling}, and Default Scaling. Perhaps most important 
    of these is Default Scaling. If you have tried to adjust the 
    scaling and have lost track of your settings, or, if you just 
    want to return to the original normal scaling settings, just 
    click on Default Scaling and then on Try. This will restore 
    AccuPoint to a "sane" condition. Remember you may use the Amiga's 
    mouse if you can't reach the gadgets with the Pen. 
 
    Special Note to AmigaDOS 3.0 Users. 
 
    If you are running AmigaDOS 3.0 or greater, you must click on 
    "Default Scaling" to return to Full Screen operation. See the 
    section titled @{" Scaling and 3.0 " link Scaling30} for complete information. 
@endnode 
@node Area "Setting the Tablet Area of Interest" 
 
                   Setting the Tablet Area of Interest 
 
    The Set Tablet Area... gadget is located two buttons down from 
    Pointer Options... in the APConfig window, see @{" Figure 2 " system "WDisplay Figure_2 TITLE Figure_2 TOP 78 LEFT 212 WIDTH 557 HEIGHT 179"}. You 
    click here to define the Area of Interest on the tablet's 
    surface. That is, the area of the tablet which you want to 
    correspond to the screen. The smaller the tablet area of interest 
    you define, the more your drawing will be magnified on the 
    screen. 
 
    Try it out by clicking on Set Tablet Area..., @{" Figure 4 " system "WDisplay Figure_4 TITLE Figure_4 TOP 132 LEFT 248 WIDTH 490 HEIGHT 187"}. 
 
    Click on Proceed - Note: the gadgets are replaced by a long 
    Display Box. 
 
    You will first notice that AccuPoint is no longer moving the 
    mouse pointer on the screen. This is normal. APConfig temporarily 
    "disconnects" AccuPoint from the Amiga. This is to remind you 
    that you are setting an area on the Tablet and not on the Screen. 
    APConfig will capture the next two clicks of the Stylus's tip 
    switch (or the Cursor's button 0) as described below and then 
    return control of the Amiga's mouse pointer to AccuPoint. 
 
    Follow the instructions in the long Display box in the Requester: 
    With the Stylus (or cursor), click first on the upper left corner 
    of a smaller area on the tablet (your Area of Interest). Then, 
    click on the lower right corner of your Area of Interest. The 
    requester will close. AccuPoint should now be back in control of 
    the mouse pointer. You should also see the message "New tablet 
    area will take effect when you click Try" in the text box. 
 
    Click "Try" to try out your new settings. 
 
    You should now find that if you place the Stylus on the upper 
    left corner of the Area of Interest which you defined, the mouse 
    pointer will be on the upper left corner of the screen. If you 
    move the Stylus to the right edge of your Area of Interest, the 
    mouse pointer should be at the right edge of the screen. 
 
    About Aspect Ratios 
 
    If your Area of Interest was not a horizontal rectangle (like the 
    Amiga screen), you may find that the lower right corner of your 
    Area of Interest doesn't exactly match the lower right of the 
    Amiga screen. This is because APConfig tries to preserve the 
    proportions of your drawing (width versus height). The proportion 
    of width to height is called the Aspect Ratio. 
 
    By default, APConfig sets the magnification scale for vertical 
    lines according to the scale for horizontal lines. That is, the Y 
    (vertical) scale is set according to the X (horizontal) scale, 
    based on the Amiga screen's Aspect Ratio. Put another way, it is 
    the width of your Tablet Area of Interest that determines its 
    height. To get a better understanding of aspect ratios, set up a 
    few different Tablet Areas of Interest in different sizes and 
    shapes. Remember to click on Try after making each change so your 
    new settings will take effect. When you have got the hang of it, 
    click on Default Scaling and then on Try to return to normal 
    settings. In the section titled @{" Coordinates and Ratios " link Aspect}, you will 
    learn how to change the aspect ratio and control how AccuPoint 
    calculates scales. 
@endnode 
@node ScreenScaling "Setting the Screen Scaling" 
 
                        Setting the Screen Scaling 
 
    The Set Screen Scaling... gadget is located just above Set Tablet 
    Area... in the APConfig window, see @{" Figure 2 " system "WDisplay Figure_2 TITLE Figure_2 TOP 78 LEFT 212 WIDTH 557 HEIGHT 179"}. Clicking on it 
    allows you to define an area of interest on the screen. The 
    effect of this is that whatever you draw in the tablet's area of 
    interest will be mapped into the screen's area of interest. In 
    fact, this is just what is happening whenever you use AccuPoint. 
    The default screen area of interest just happens to be the size 
    of the whole Amiga screen. The effect of Set Screen Scaling... 
    will usually be to reduce what you draw in size. 
 
    NOTE: When you change the screen scaling you will often find that 
    you cannot reach all areas of the screen. Remember, you are 
    defining an area of interest on the screen which is smaller than 
    the whole screen. You may find that you "run out of tablet" when 
    trying to reach the edge of the screen. Remember, you can always 
    use the Amiga's mouse to reach a menu or gadget you may need. You 
    will probably find that you will use Set Tablet Area... more 
    often, as its function is more general purpose in nature. Now, 
    let's try Screen Scaling. 
 
    Click on Set Screen Scaling..., see @{" Figure 5 " system "WDisplay Figure_5 TITLE Figure_5 TOP 114 LEFT 236 WIDTH 489 HEIGHT 186"}. 
 
    A requester should appear containing instructions. The procedure 
    will be similar to Set Tablet Area... . This time, APConfig will 
    only disconnect the Pen's buttons, not the positioning of the 
    mouse pointer. This allows you to use the Amiga's mouse to bring 
    another window to the front (such as a paint program) so you can 
    better see what you want as your area of interest. Again, the 
    next two clicks of the Stylus's tip switch will define your area 
    of interest. Clicking with the Amiga's mouse buttons will 
    function as usual and will not define your area of interest. 
 
    Click on Proceed - Note: the gadgets are replaced by a long 
    Display Box. 
 
    Now, using the Amiga's mouse, re-arrange your windows if 
    necessary. 
 
    Using the Stylus, place the mouse pointer on the upper left 
    corner of a smaller area of the screen (your Screen Area of 
    Interest) and click once. 
 
    Still using the Stylus, move the mouse pointer to the lower right 
    corner of your screen area of interest and click once more. 
 
    APConfig will now return normal button functions to the Pen. 
 
    Go back to the APConfig window and click on Try to try your new 
    settings. 
 
    You should find that the mouse pointer's area of movement is 
    reduced. At this point you will probably find that this situation 
    isn't very useful. 
 
    Click on Default Scaling and then Try to return to normal 
    settings. 
 
    You may feel that didn't accomplished much. In a moment, we will 
    try a practical application of scaling. 
@endnode 
@node Scaling30 "Scaling and AmigaDOS 3.0" 
 
                     Scaling and AmigaDOS 3.0 
 
    Several years ago when TriMedia developed the original tablet 
    driver software on which AccuPoint is based, Commodore was about 
    to release AmigaDOS 2.0. While 2.0 had some support for tablet 
    drivers in its original design, we found to our dismay that it 
    had been only partially implemented. There were also certain 
    pitfalls which could not have been anticipated until someone (us) 
    tried to actually use these new features in the Amiga operating 
    system. Most significant of these was a lack any method for an 
    application to receive pressure data. Most all of these 
    deficiencies were addressed in AmigaDOS 3.0. However, 2.0 users 
    don't have access to the tablet features in the 3.0 ROMs. 
    TriMedia's AccuPoint open tablet interface standard provides the 
    means to provide most 3.0 tablet features on 2.0 systems. 
    However, certain differences remain. These are outlined below and 
    deal mostly with Scaling. 
 
    Scaling with AmigaDOS 2.0 
 
    On Amiga systems running pre-3.0 versions of the operating 
    system, AccuPoint always reports the pointer's position based on 
    a screen resolution of 640x400 (overscan not withstanding), 
    regardless of the actual screen mode in use. The Amiga system 
    then adjusts the pointer position accordingly. The downside of 
    this is that when using a higher resolution display such as 
    SuperHires mode, you can only "hit" every OTHER pixel. You will 
    still draw solid lines. You just can't position the pointer on 
    each individual pixel as you can with the mouse. Note that this 
    on only a problem on screens with a non-overscan resolution 
    greater than 640x400. 
 
    Scaling with 3.0 
 
    On Amiga systems running version 3.0 or greater of the operating 
    system, AccuPoint is aware of the actual resolution of the screen 
    so each pixel is individually accessible. 
 
    Under 3.0, the "Default Scaling" gadget has an additional 
    function. Due the the different scaling methods employed in 3.0, 
    you will find that if you have set a "Screen Scaling" area you 
    will have to click on Default Scaling before you can reliably use 
    the full screen area. Under 2.0, you can return to full screen 
    scaling by simply doing a "Set Screen Scaling..." function and 
    setting the screen area to maximum. If you do this under 3.0, you 
    may not be able to access the overscan area of other screens 
    later. Therefor, when you are done using a reduced screen scaling 
    area, YOU MUST CLICK ON "DEFAULT SCALING" TO RETURN TO FULL 
    SCREEN MODE. 
@endnode 
@node ScalingFunctions "Using the Scaling Functions Together" 
 
                   Using the Scaling Functions Together 
 
    Try this short tutorial to get a feel for the real-world uses of 
    scaling. You will need some sort of paint program. For our 
    purposes here we will discuss Electronic Arts Deluxe Paint, but 
    any paint program will do. 
 
    First, set the @{" Pixel Aspect Ratio " link Aspect} control to Display (or Square 
    if you are on the PAL system and running AmigaDOS 2.0/2.1), and 
    the Specified Aspect to Width. 
 
    Find a simple line drawing in a newspaper or magazine (a couple 
    of inches square) and clip it out. 
 
    Place it under the clear overlay on the tablet's active area (or 
    tape it to the surface). 
 
    Start your paint program. Pick any non-overscan screen mode. 
 
    Draw an outline rectangle a couple of inches wide on the screen. 
    Make its proportions similar to your clipping. 
 
    Return to APConfig and execute the @{" Set Tablet Area " link Area} function as 
    described above. Set the area of interest to the upper left and 
    lower right corners of your clipping. 
 
    DO NOT click Try yet! 
 
    Execute the @{" Set Screen Scaling " link ScreenScaling} function in APConfig as described 
    above. This time, after clicking on Proceed, use the Amiga's 
    mouse to bring your paint program to the front. Set the screen 
    area of interest to the upper left and lower right corners of the 
    rectangle you drew earlier. 
 
    Return to APConfig and click on Try. 
 
    Now, switch back to your paint program. Using the freehand 
    drawing tool and the smallest brush size trace the clipping on 
    the tablet. Concentrate on guiding the Stylus over the clipping 
    on the tablet and not on the screen. When you have finished a few 
    outlines, check the results on the screen. They should be 
    similar. If they aren't, return to Default Scaling and try 
    setting the scales again. You may have missed a click or 
    unintentionally double clicked somewhere. 
 
    Tracing accurately requires some practice. The Stylus still isn't 
    exactly like a regular pen, but it's close. Where scaling really 
    shines is when used with a structured drawing program. An example 
    would be creating your own fonts for your favorite 3D or desktop 
    publishing application. You probably won't use scaling every day, 
    but it's a big help when you need it. 
 
    Setting Pen Sensitivity 
 
    As mentioned above, you can use @{" Set Tablet Area " link Area} to simulate the 
    effects of the mouse speed control in Preferences. By setting the 
    tablet area to a small size, you increase the "speed" of the 
    Stylus. When working with a very small tablet area, it's a good 
    idea to cut out a piece of paper of the same size and place it 
    under the clear overlay on the tablet. This makes it much easier 
    to find your "live" area on the tablet. 
@endnode 
@node Serial "Setting the Serial Port" 
 
                         Setting the Serial Port 
 
    The button gadget labeled "Set Port & Modes..." opens a requester 
    that allows you to assign which Serial Port and Unit, see 
    @{" Figure 6 " system "WDisplay Figure_6 TITLE Figure_6 TOP 275 LEFT 83 WIDTH 336 HEIGHT 156"}, AccuPoint will use for communications with the Tablet. 
 
    The Serial Port name should be entered into the string gadget 
    labeled "Device Name". The Port number should be entered into the 
    gadget labeled "Unit". The name of the device for the built in 
    Amiga serial port is "serial.device" and the Unit should be "0". 
    If you are using a multi-port serial board, the Name and Unit 
    number for your serial board can be found in the documentation 
    that came with your board. 
 
    The other gadgets in the window are explained in the section 
    @{" Coordinates and Ratios " link Aspect}. 
@endnode 
@node Aspect "Coordinates and Ratios" 
 
                          Coordinates and Ratios 
 
    The button gadget labeled "Ports & Modes..." opens a requester 
    that allows you to change the way AccuPoint handles the Aspect 
    Ratio and change coordinate the mode from Absolute to Relative, 
    see @{" Figure 6 " system "WDisplay Figure_6 TITLE Figure_6 TOP 275 LEFT 83 WIDTH 336 HEIGHT 156"}. 
 
    It may surprise you to learn that the tiny dots (pixels) that 
    make up an image on the Amiga aren't always square. The "Pixel 
    Aspect Ratio:" gadget allows you to tell AccuPoint what their 
    proportions are, on your intended output device (video monitor, 
    printer etc.). The "Pixel Aspect Ratio:" gadget cycles between 
    these three settings: 
 
        · Display 
        · Square 
        · Free X/Y 
 
        · Display: (Default) If you are running AmigaDOS 2.0/2.1 and 
        are on the NTSC television standard (like USA), and you are 
        going to show your work on video through a genlock, you will 
        probably want to use the "Display" setting. Under 3.0, you 
        should use "Display" regardless of which television standard 
        you are on. AccuPoint will automatically adjust. 
 
        · Square: If you are running AmigaDOS 2.0/2.1 and are on the 
        PAL video standard, or will be printing your work on a laser 
        printer, typesetter, or other square pixel device you should 
        try the "Square" setting. 
 
        · Free X/Y: The "Free X/Y" setting disables aspect ratio 
        control and allows you to intentionally distort, or force fit 
        one area of the tablet into another area of the screen. Used 
        with the scaling functions, Free X/Y allows you to change the 
        proportions of a drawing as you trace. 
 
    The "Specified Aspect:" gadget cycles between these two settings 
    and is only active if Pixel Aspect Ratio is NOT set to Free X/Y: 
 
        · Width - APConfig will compute the VERTICAL scale, based on 
        the HORIZONTAL scale AND your selected pixel aspect ratio. 
 
        · Height - APConfig will compute the HORIZONTAL scale, based 
        on the VERTICAL scale AND your selected pixel aspect ratio. 
 
    The "Coordinate Mode:" gadget cycles between these two settings: 
 
        · Absolute - the mouse pointer will track the Stylus, even if 
        it is lifted from the Tablet and returned to the Tablet in a 
        different position. The mouse pointer will snap to a 
        corresponding new position on the screen when the stylus is 
        brought back into proximity. This mode makes it possible to 
        accurately trace existing artwork. 
 
        · Relative (Mouse Mode) - when the Stylus is lifted and 
        returned to the Tablet, the mouse pointer position will not 
        change, allowing you to use the Stylus in the same way you 
        use the mouse. NOTE: You should NOT use this mode for tracing 
        as the absolute position will be lost. 
 
    The other gadgets in the window are explained in the section 
    @{" Setting the Serial Port " link Serial}. 
@endnode 
@node FineTuning "Fine Tuning Performance With Priority and Data Rate" 
 
           Fine Tuning Performance With Priority and Data Rate 
 
    About Multitasking 
 
    As you probably already know, the Amiga is a multitasking 
    computer. This simply means that it can run more than one program 
    at a time. The AccuPoint Driver is, in fact, just a program that 
    multitasks with your other applications software (paint programs, 
    etc.). Whenever the Stylus is in proximity, the AccuPoint Driver 
    program is running, processing data from the Tablet and telling 
    the Amiga system where the mouse pointer should be. The faster 
    the Tablet sends data, the more CPU (processing) time the 
    AccuPoint driver needs to act on the data. In a multitasking 
    system like the Amiga, the more programs there are running at 
    once (performing work), the slower the system performs any one 
    task. If one program has a lot of work to perform, it may "load 
    down" the system, making the whole computer seem to run slowly. 
    Each program running on the Amiga has a certain Priority. When a 
    high priority program has work to perform it can interrupt a 
    program with a lower priority. Most programs run at priority 0 
    which means that they all get the same attention when they have 
    work to perform. 
 
    AccuPoint and Multitasking 
 
    The AccuPoint software provides two ways to adjust how it shares 
    the Amiga's resources with other programs. Using APConfig you can 
    control both the AccuPoint Driver's priority, and the rate at 
    which the Tablet sends position information to the Amiga. As in 
    most things, the key is to reach a good compromise between the 
    two. 
@endnode 
@node Rate "Setting Data Rate" 
 
                          Setting Data Rate 
 
    The APConfig window contains a slider gadget labeled Data Rate, 
    See @{" Figure 2 "  system "WDisplay Figure_2 TITLE Figure_2 TOP 78 LEFT 212 WIDTH 557 HEIGHT 179"}. Sliding the gadget's knob right or left will 
    increase or decrease the rate at which the Tablet sends data. The 
    current rate setting is displayed to the right of the gadget. The 
    number displayed is the number of X/Y coordinate pairs the Tablet 
    will send each second. A higher number will provide smoother 
    movement of the mouse pointer, but will also place a heavier load 
    on the system. This can be seen when drawing in a paint program, 
    especially with a large brush. At high data rates, the mouse 
    pointer may lag behind your movements slightly. If your paint 
    program has a "Follow Mouse" option, this may help. A lower data 
    rate will produce more choppy, staccato movement, but will have 
    little impact on system performance. The default is 40 pps (pairs 
    per second). This provides a good balance of performance versus 
    smoothness. Settings higher than 50 or 60 will have little 
    improvement in smoothness. You will probably find settings lower 
    than 25 too jumpy for smooth drawing. 
 
    The Factory default for Data Rate is 40pps. This setting is 
    recommended for stock, 68000 based Amigas (A500 and A2000). A 
    setting of 60pps is recommended for accelerated Amigas and those 
    based on the 68020, 68030 or 68040 (A1200, A2500, A3000 & A4000). 
@endnode 
@node Priority "Setting the AccuPoint Driver Priority" 
 
                  Setting the AccuPoint Driver Priority 
 
    The Priority gadget is located just above the Data Rate gadget in 
    the APConfig window. By dragging the gadget's knob right or left 
    you can increase or decrease the priority at which the AccuPoint 
    Driver is running. Settings range between 0 and 10. Since most 
    applications run at 0 priority, you will find that in most cases, 
    it only matters whether AccuPoint is running at 0 or above 0. 
    Certain applications, however, do use other priorities. Certain 
    rendering and animation programs are some examples. 
 
    The default setting of 4 seems to provide good all around 
    operation. We STRONGLY recommend that you do not change the 
    priority from this setting unless you have VERY GOOD reason to do 
    so. 
@endnode 
@node Specs "Technical Specifications" 
 
                         Technical Specifications 
 
    Software 
 
    Default Settings (Software) 
 
        Tablet Type ........... SD-510C 
        Pointer Type .......... Pressure Pen 
        Button Functions: 
            Tip Switch ........ Left mouse button 
            Menu Key .......... <Left-Alt> 
        Draw Pressure ......... 50 / 255 
        Click Pressure ........ 150 / 255 
        Priority .............. 4 
        Data Rate ............. 40 coordinate pairs per second 
        Tablet Area ........... 1" less than active area width, 
        centered on tablet (1/2" active margins) 
        Screen Scaling ........ Full 
 
@endnode 
@node Assistance "If You Need Assistance" 
 
                          If You Need Assistance 
 
    We have made every effort to ensure that AccuPoint will be 
    reliable and that this manual is clear. However, nothing's 
    perfect. If you should have any problems with operating your 
    tablet, you can contact our Technical Support department at the 
    phone number and address below. We do ask however, that you check 
    the manual first. The answers to most questions can be found in 
    these pages, saving you the cost of a phone call. If you have 
    checked the manual and still have not resolved the problem please 
    write or call us at the following: 
 
                        TriMedia, Inc. 
                        AccuPoint Technical Support 
                        60 East Hintz Road 
                        Wheeling, IL 60090 
 
    Technical Support Phone Number: (708) 520-7502 
    There is no charge for technical support. 
 
    Please include or have available the following information: 
 
        · A detailed description of the problem. 
        · The brand and model of tablet you are using. 
        · The version number of your AccuPoint software (see the 
        APConfig menu bar). 
        · Your software serial number. 
        · The version of Kickstart and Workbench you are using (1.3, 
        2.0 etc.). 
        · Your Amiga's configuration (model, memory, disk(s), etc.). 
        · The name and version of the program (if any) with which you 
        are having a problem (i.e. Deluxe Paint IV AGA). 
 
    We will try to resolve any problems you may have with AccuPoint 
    as expediently as possible. 
@endnode 
