@node Digitizer 
@prev Digitizer 
 
A digitizing tablet is an absolute positioning device. This means 
that if you lift the pen off the drawing surface, move it, and put 
the pen back down, the mouse pointer on screen will move to reflect 
the new position. Compare that with the mouse. If you pick it up, 
move it, and replace it, the mouse pointer will not move. This 
positioning system allows you to trace existing artwork without 
losing track of your position. 
 
    Press Retrace. 
@next Digitizer 
@endnode 
@node AccuPoint 
@prev AccuPoint 
 
    The AccuPoint(TM) software package is comprised of three 
    programs: 
 
        The AccuPoint Driver is a software program that communicates 
        with the Tablet and converts the positions of the Pointing 
        Device on the tablet's surface to mouse positions, which move 
        the mouse cursor on the screen. 
 
        APConfig(TM) is a Preferences type configuration program 
        which allows you to customize the AccuPoint Driver to your 
        needs. 
 
        APExit(TM) is a program which will shutdown the AccuPoint 
        Driver and remove it from memory. 
 
    This guide explains the AccuPoint driver and the configuration 
    program, APConfig. 
 
    Press Retrace. 
@next AccuPoint 
@endnode 
@node Features "Features" 
@prev Features 
 
                Some Key Features of AccuPoint(TM). 
 
    · Save Settings 
    · Support for Multi-port Serial Boards 
    · Selectable Aspect Ratios 
    · Absolute and Mouse Mode 
    · Online Manual 
 
    Support for Pressure Sensitive Tablets 
    AccuPoint is the first tablet driver to bring pressure support to 
    the Amiga computer. When used with pressure-aware applications 
    such as DeluxePaint IV AGA or OpalPaint, you can vary your brush 
    size, translucency, etc. on the fly, by varying the pressure you 
    apply to the stylus's pen point. AccuPoint also brings advanced 
    AmigaDOS 3.0 tablet features to users of AmigaDOS 2.0/2.1. 
 
    Support for Multi-port Serial Boards 
    The AccuPoint software supports multi-port serial boards. If you 
    have such a board in your system, you may use one of its ports to 
    connect your tablet to the Amiga leaving the built-in port free 
    for other devices. This has been tested with the ASDG Dual Serial 
    Board. See the section @{" Setting the Serial Port " link Serial} for more 
    information. 
 
    Selectable Aspect Ratio 
    You can adjust AccuPoint to better match the pixel aspect ratio 
    of your intended output device (video, printer etc.). Gadgets in 
    APConfig allow you to select between: 
 
        "Display", (default) for video output. 
 
        "Square", for some print work and special applications. 
 
        "Free X/Y", free form scaling for intentional distortion 
        effects. 
 
    APConfig also lets you determine which axis (width or height) you 
    will specify and which will be computed for you when scaling. See 
    the section titled @{" Coordinates and Ratios " link Aspect} for more information. 
 
    Absolute and Mouse Mode 
    In Absolute mode, the Pen always moves the mouse pointer to a 
    position on the screen proportional to where the pen is on the 
    tablet. In Relative mode, the Pen behaves more like a mouse. If 
    lifted off the Tablet, when returned to a different location, the 
    mouse pointer will not move. This allows you to pick up the Pen, 
    move it over, and continue to move the mouse pointer in the same 
    direction. 
 
    Online Manual 
    The online manual is authored in AmigaGuide. AmigaGuide is a 
    Commodore supplied hypertext viewing program. This will become 
    Commodore's standard way of viewing text documents, eventually 
    replacing "More". AmigaOS 2.1 users will find that the program is 
    called AmigaGuide, and 3.0 users will find that the program is 
    called MultiView. Both programs will display this document, and 
    AmigaGuide is included on the disk with this release for users of 
    older operating system versions. 
 
    Press Retrace. 
@next New 
@endnode 
@node Figures "Displaying Figures" 
@prev Figures 
 
                            Displaying Figures 
    When a button appears in the text referring to a Figure, pressing 
    that button will display a small window with the graphic of that 
    figure. If gadgets are displayed as part of that graphic, they 
    will not be functional. To close the window, press the Close 
    gadget in the upper left corner. 
 
    Press Retrace. 
@next Figures 
@endnode 
